=========================================
std::move (C++11) - INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is std::move?
----------------------
std::move is NOT a move operation.

👉 It is a type cast that converts an object into an rvalue reference.

It allows resources of an object to be "moved" instead of copied.

Header:
#include <utility>

-----------------------------------------
2. Important Concept (MOST ASKED)
-----------------------------------------
std::move does NOT move anything.

It only enables move semantics.

Actual move happens via:
👉 move constructor / move assignment operator

-----------------------------------------
3. Why std::move is needed?
-----------------------------------------
Copying:
- expensive (deep copy)

Moving:
- transfers ownership of resources
- avoids copying

Example:
string a = "Hello";
string b = std::move(a);

Now:
b = "Hello"
a = (valid but empty/undefined state)

-----------------------------------------
4. What happens internally?
-----------------------------------------
Before move:
a ---> "Hello"

After std::move:
b ---> "Hello"
a ---> empty state

No memory copying happens.

-----------------------------------------
5. Syntax
-----------------------------------------
T&& = rvalue reference

std::move(x)

Equivalent to:
static_cast<T&&>(x)

-----------------------------------------
6. Example
-----------------------------------------
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <utility>

int main()
{
    std::vector<int> v1 = {1,2,3,4};

    std::vector<int> v2 = std::move(v1);

    std::cout << "v2 size: " << v2.size() << std::endl;
    std::cout << "v1 size: " << v1.size() << std::endl; // valid but empty

    return 0;
}

-----------------------------------------
7. After std::move
-----------------------------------------
Object becomes:
✔ valid
❌ but unspecified state

Important:
You can safely:
- destroy it
- assign new value
- reuse it

But:
❌ do NOT assume its contents

-----------------------------------------
8. When is std::move used?
-----------------------------------------
✔ Returning large objects
✔ Avoid copying vectors/strings
✔ Transfer ownership (unique_ptr)
✔ STL optimizations

-----------------------------------------
9. std::move vs copy
-----------------------------------------

Copy:
- duplicates data
- O(n)

Move:
- transfers pointer/resources
- O(1)

-----------------------------------------
10. Move Constructor Example
-----------------------------------------
class A {
public:
    A(A&& obj) {
        // steal resources
    }
};

std::move triggers move constructor.

-----------------------------------------
11. Common Mistake (VERY IMPORTANT)
-----------------------------------------
❌ std::move makes object faster

✔ WRONG

Correct:
std::move only allows move, it does not guarantee it.

-----------------------------------------
12. When NOT to use std::move
-----------------------------------------
❌ Do NOT use on:
- local variables you still need
- return value optimization cases
- small objects (may be slower)

-----------------------------------------
13. std::move does NOT move:
-----------------------------------------
❌ memory itself
❌ data physically
❌ objects automatically

It only casts to rvalue reference.

-----------------------------------------
14. Real-world analogy
-----------------------------------------
Copy:
Photocopy document

Move:
Give original document and empty your file

-----------------------------------------
15. ONE-LINE INTERVIEW ANSWER
-----------------------------------------
std::move is a utility that casts an object to an rvalue reference, enabling move semantics so that resources can be transferred instead of copied, improving performance for large objects.
